summary.seg: This manuscript is a composite volume with its Parts deriving from 9 separate original sources written in England and Italy between the 11th and 15th centuries. Part 1 is a set of medieval endleaves with notes, annotations, and lists of the contents, Parts 2-8 contain medical treatises in Latin, and Part 9 is another set of medieval endleaves that preserve damaged copies of letters from a Carmelite foundation in England as well as a number of smaller and more informal annotations.

Peterhouse MS 251 appears to have reached its current composite form after two distinct phases of compilation, the first of which seems to have brought together Parts 1-7, and the second of which seems to have added Parts 8-9 to Parts 1-7. Precisely how and when Peterhouse MS 251 Parts 1-7 were brought together is unknown, but they seem to have been together by 8 December 1330, the date of a Caucio note on f. i verso (a medieval endleaf). This note is partly illegible due to rubbing, but the remaining text can be read as 'Caucio Walteri de Wasten exponitur ciste Batulfi ... concepionis beate Marie anno Domini Mo CCCo xxx', i.e., the book was pledged as surety for a loan and placed in Botolph's chest on 8 December 1330 by Walter de Wasten. Caucio inscriptions in manuscripts reflect a practice common (but not limited) to Oxford and Cambridge in the 14th and 15th centuries, where borrowers could pledge books or other high-value items in exchange for a monetary loan. The lender would add a description of the loan to the item (or presumably add a label to non-codex pledges) usually beginning with the word 'Caucio' or 'Cautio' (pledge/security) followed by details such as the date, the amount loaned, and the original owner of the item, and would then store the deposit in a chest for the duration of the loan, which borrowers could redeem on repayment. The loan chests and their funds were often initially supplied by a single benefactor, and the chest that they endowed usually bore their name thereafter. In this example, 'ciste Batulfi' is probably a reference to 'St Botoloph's Chest', which was established by Thomas de St Botolph, parson of South Dalton in Yorkshire and personal clerk to John le Romeyn (d. 1296), archbishop of York. Thomas was still alive in 1293 and the chest was probably founded at some point afterwards. It operated until at least 1347. If this identification is correct, it places at least some parts of Peterhouse MS 251 in Cambridge in 1330. The Caucio inscription on f. i verso is briefly discussed in Thomson's Catalogue, p. 158; Thomson does not mention the location of Botolph's Chest in Cambridge, but he makes a Cambridge connection for the Caucio inscription as he suggests that 'Walteri de Wasten' may be the Walter de Weston in Emden BRUC, p. 631, a cleric of Cambridge who complained about the violence from the mayor and townspeople of Cambridge in 1322 as recorded in Calendar of the Patent Rolls preserved in the Public Record Office 1216-1509 (1891-1916).

Underneath the Caucio inscription on f. i verso and in a late 14th- or 15th-century hand is a medieval list of the contents of the volume. This enumerates 12 items, the final one of which - 'liber de ffebribus' - was added by another, probably 15th-century hand and almost certainly refers to the texts on ff. 106-191 (i.e., Part 8). The work now known as Galen's Ad glauconem de medendi methodo (not to be confused with the larger Galenic text now known as the Therapeutica or De methodo medendi, which in the Middle Ages was usually known as the Ars magna or the Megategni), was a treatise on fevers addressed to Galen's nephew or friend Glauco(n), and was often known in the Middle Ages by the title 'Liber de febribus' or 'De febribus ad Glauconem'. On folio 106r, in the upper margin, a late 14th or early 15th century hand has also added a title for the text,'liber de ffebribus'. The last original entry in the medieval list of the contents then is 'Pronostica ypocratis incompletus', which seems to be a reference to the Prognostica of Hippocrates on ff. 102v-105r, which is complete, but which is immediately followed by an incomplete copy of Theophilus' De urinis, which begins near the bottom of a column of text on f. 105r with a rubric similar in size and distinction to the internal subheadings in the preceding text. As such, it seems to have been read by the main compiler of the medieval list of the contents of the volume as an incomplete final section of the Prognostica.

It seems likely that Parts 8-9 joined Parts 1-7 at Peterhouse during the 15th century. Part 9 is a medieval bifolium that preserves copies of two letters by a single scribe, one of which is dated to 1400 in the text. Part 9 is badly damaged through rubbing and use as a pastedown and endleaves, but in addition to the copies of the letters, it also preserves several informal annotations including names and accompanying 15th century dates. It is possible that Part 9 was added by itself to the volume, perhaps for a late 15th-century or 16th-century rebinding, but given that the 'liber de ffebribus' entry in the medieval table of contents on f. i verso is in a different (?15th century) hand, it seems probable that Parts 8 and 9 were joined to Parts 1-7 in the 15th century, with Part 8 added due to the similarity of its content to Parts 2-7 and Part 9 as a protective wrapper for the new end of the volume.

A portion of the manuscript (almost certainly Parts 1-7) were given to Peterhouse in 1385 by William Irby William Irby , a Fellow of Peterhouse; Irby's donation is recorded in the upper margin of f. 1r - 'Memorandum quod magister Willelmus Irby socius domus Sancti Petri contulit istum librum eidem domui anno Domini MCCC lxxxvto' (Memorandum that master William Irby fellow of Peterhouse brought this book to the same house in A.D. 1385). Parts 8 and 9 must have joined the rest of the volume after Parts 1-7 had been absorbed into the Peterhouse library collection, and so it seems likely that Parts 8 and 9 were also donated by a member of the Peterhouse community.

All of the Parts of this manuscript are interesting in their own right as well as when they are considered in their composite arrangement, but Dr Debby Banham has discussed the specific significance of Part 8 (ff. 106r-191v for the study of the history of medicine in England, and in particular within the context of the reception of Classical medical texts in medieval England. Dr Banham described the contents of Part 8 as 'the nearest thing to a standard medical textbook in early medieval Europe', i.e., for the study of medicine in Europe before it became a profession studied and researched at the new universities. Dr Banham has also pointed out that Peterhouse MS 251, ff. 106r-191v contains the 'earliest surviving English manuscript of Galen's Ad Glauconem de methodo medendi, and also of the pseudo-Galenic Liber tertius which travels with it, and of the Libri Aurelii and Esculapii, two works frequently found with the Galen complex, as here.' Although the origin of Part 8 has not been established with total certainty, in all likelihood, Peterhouse MS 251 Part 8 (ff. 106r-191v) was copied at the abbey of St Augustine's in Canterbury, and the quires are emblematic of a new style of medical study and enquiry in England that was to become a feature of the standard of scientific learning available at the wealthiest monastic houses in England in the 12th and 13th centuries.

Dr Sarah Gilbert
Project Cataloguer for the Curious Cures Project
Cambridge University Library

supportDesc.support: All medieval leaves parchment; modern handmade-paper pastedowns and endleaves added in 2023.

foliation.note: Foliated in the upper outer corner of each recto in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals, ff. i + 1-192. The outermost medieval parchment flyleaves (ff. [ia] and [193] were pastedowns until September 2023 and as such were not included in the folio designation scheme present in the volume; these leaves have been assigned temporary designations in order to produce a functional TEI-XML catalogue record, and those designtions are enclosed in [square brackets] throughout this record. The modern handmade paper flyleaves added to the beginning and end of the volume as part of the 2023 conservation and rebinding work have been assigned temporary designations ff. [a]-[b] and ff. [c]-[d] respectively. Note that the modern paper endleaves ff. [a]-[b] and [c]-[d] do not appear in the digital image set for Peterhouse MS 251.

note.p: A note on f. i recto, partially erased: 'liber florum et Regularum Magistri aflaticii de monte pesulano breuiter gyl[?]'. The note refers to the text on ff. 27r-48v, which is attributed to a Magister Afratisius/Alfacius of Monte Pesulano (Montpellier) in the incipits and explicits supplied with the text now known as the Practica sometimes attributed to Copho.

binding.p: Rebound in September 2023 by James Cassels. Tawed goat skin over quarter-sawn oak boards. Two silver pin-and-ring fore edge fastenings with tawed goatskin and vellum straps. Four raised bands on spine; double linen cords fitted to the medieval sewing stations. Head and tail bands of linen and finished with decorative sewing of alternate blue and cream segments.
Handmade paper pastedowns pasted over the turn ins. Two handmade paper endleaves (unphotographed) added at each end of the volume, ff. [a]-[b] and [c]-[d] respectively, all blank.
Medieval parchment pastedowns lifted; the newly free leaves assigned the designations ff. [ia] and [163] respectively.

Peterhouse MS 251 is now stored in an archival box made from acid free mill board, covered with archival buckram, and lined with museum board. The box also contains an archival folder which contains the remains of the 18th century binding and a printed description by James Cassels of the conservation and rebinding work undertaken in 2023.
Binding dimensions (L x W x D): 255 x 180 x 55 mm

18th century binding preserved in an archival folder stored in the manuscript box after the September 2023 rebinding. Undecorated parchment cover over thin rope fibre boards. Boards attached to text block by laced in cords glued into 3 deep saw-cuts across the spine.

List of the contents of the volume written in ink on the spine in an 18th century hand, now badly rubbed and partially illegible. A former ?shelfmark or designation in ink on the in the same hand as the 18th century list of the contents on the spine: '2-5-2'. Faint note in pencil 'James 210' for the catalogue number of this volume in the Ecloga of Thomas James (1600). Small printed paper label fixed to spine bearing the shelfmark designation '251'.
Traces of pre-18th century binding(?s) still visible in the volume.
Four raised bands made for an earlier binding visible on spine; double-twisted tawed leather supports cut at the joints.
Traces of fittings for a former fastening or chain staple visible in the centre of the tail edge of ff. [ia]-i and 192-[193].

history.acquisition: Some Parts of this manuscript (probably Parts 1-7) given by fellow of Peterhouse, William (de) Irby (Venn ACAD no. IRBY374W) in 1385. The donation is recorded on f. 1r: Memorandum quod magister Willelmus Irby socius domus Sancti Petri contulit istum librum eidem domui anno Domini MCCC lxxxvto (Memorandum that master William Irby fellow of Peterhouse brought this book to the same house in A.D. 1385). Parts 8 and 9 probably added after 1400 through an unknown donation.

availability.p: The manuscripts of Peterhouse are stored on long-term deposit at Cambridge University Library. Readers wishing to consult a Peterhouse manuscript in-person will need to visit the University Library. Entry to read in Cambridge University Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

origin.origDate: The oldest annotations on these leaves probably date from the 13th century or perhaps the late 12th. The Caucio inscription on f. i verso is dated '1330' and so ff. [ia]- i were almost certainly with some of the remainder of the volume as endleaves by that date.
origin.origPlace: Probably written in England. There is a Caucio inscription on f. i verso which refers to a loan chest located in Cambridge.

provenance.p: A note on f. i verso, badly rubbed: 'Caucio Walteri de Wasten exponitur ciste Batulfi ... concepionis beate Marie anno Domini Mo CCCo xxx', i.e., the book was pledged as surety for a loan and placed in Botolph's chest on 8 December 1330 by Walter de Wasten. Caucio inscriptions in manuscripts reflect a practice common (but not limited) to Oxford and Cambridge in the 14th and 15th centuries where borrowers could pledge books or other high-value items in exchange for a monetary loan supplied by a lender who would store the manuscript in a chest for the duration of the loan. The loan chests and their funds were often supplied by a single benefactor whose name became associated with the chest long after their death and became incorporated into the Caucio inscriptions usually in the form 'ciste [name]'; in this case, the 'ciste Batulfi' probably refers to a loan-chest in Cambridge known as 'Botoloph's Chest', which, if that identification is correct, places at least some parts of Peterhouse MS 251 in Cambridge in December 1330. 'Botolph's Chest' was supposedly endowed by a Thomas de St Botolph, chaplain to John Le Romeyn, archbishop of York, see Fuller and Billingfield, 'Section IV' in The History of the University of Cambridge, esp. p. 130.

This Caucio note is briefly discussed in Thomson's Catalogue, p. 158; Thomson suggests that 'Walteri de Wasten' may be the Walter de Weston in Emden BRUC, p. 631, a cleric of Cambridge who complained about the violence from the mayor and townspeople of Cambridge in 1322 as recorded in Calendar of the Patent Rolls preserved in the Public Record Office 1216-1509, 54 vols (1891-1916).

The Caucio note is also briefly discussed in CBMLC 10 UC48.291 where the note is transcribed as follows: 'Caucio Walter de Kasten exspositus ciste Botulph' Concepionis beate Marie anno Domini Mo ccco xxx'

layout.seg: Ruled in two-column format, frame and lines, in faint leadpoint. Typically 50 lines to the column and usually written above top line.

handNote.p: Written in a late and compressed Caroline minuscule of ?southern ?Italian appearance. For the items where there is a main text accompanied by a gloss or a commentary - the 'main' text is written in a larger and more calligraphic style, usually a few sentences at a time, and then the gloss or commentary follows underneath in a smaller and plainer style.

decoNote.p: Major initials at the opening of each text: gold initials on a red and blue geometric ground, the grounds further decorated with flourishes in white, and red pen-flourishing extending from the frame of the initial along the length of the adjacent margin, e.g., f. 49v.
Minor initials in red or blue at the minor divisions of the text, occasionally with very minor pen-flourishing.
Some minor initials in gold, usually marking a new significant section within a text, e.g., f. 70r.
Headings, section titles and key words in red in the main text or in the margins.
Paraph marks in red and blue to mark the smallest sub-divisions of the text.

origin.origPlace: Possibly written in ?Southern ?Italy. Place of origin suggested based on palaeographical features.

msItem.title: Copy of a letter written in 1400 to John and Alicia Horssyngton from a Carmelite foundation

note.p: The letter greets 'John Horssyngton et Aliccie uxori sue' (John Horssyngton and Alicia his wife) and concludes with a dating clause 'Anno domini MCCCCo', i.e., the year 1400.
The text of the letter is badly damaged and partly illegible due to rubbing. There is an annotation under the letter in a 15th century English cursive minuscule, now illegible due to rubbing.

msItem.title: Copy of a letter (?from a Carmelite foundation)

note.p: The leaf was once used as a pastedown and most of the text is illegible due to adhesive residue and rubbing.

The text of the letter is in the same hand as the letter on f. 192r and presumably shares some origin and context features with that letter, but names, dates, and location information in the letter are too damaged to read with any certainty.
There is an annotation in a 15th century English cursive minuscule under the main text of the letter - this appears to be the same annotator who added a note in a similar location on f. 192r.

signatures.p: No leaf signatures particular to this Part.
No quire signatures particular to this Part.

catchwords.seg: No catchwords particular to this Part.

supportDesc.condition: The two leaves in this part are a bifolium. Folio [193] was used as the rear pastedown in a former binding and is coated in an adhesive residue. All surfaces in the bifolium are badly rubbed and most of the text is illegible or gone entirely. Folio 193 was repaired with strong Japanaese paper in 2023 as part of a program of conservation and rebinding work.

p.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame and lines. Folios 192r and [193] verso ruled in single-column format; the 'text box' is only ruled for the number of lines necessary for the text rather than to the lower bound, so e.g., there is an unruled space of c. 45mm in the lower portion of the text box on f. 192r. Folios 192v-[193] recto have margin ruling but no line ruling and are informally written.

handNote.p: The copies of the letters on ff. 192r and [193] verso are written in a formal northern textualis.

decoNote.p: Folios 192r and [193] verso: significant initials in black ink with decorative flourishes in black and red.

note.p:
Folios 192v-[193] recto: informal annotations written by ?three scribes in formal northern textualis with further annotations in an informal minuscule, all of 15th century appearance. The annotations on this opening are mostly written 90Â° clockwise and anticlockwise relative to the 'normal' orientiation of the book. Annotations as follows:
'Dyllforde (?Dylsforde) anno domini ...'
'Roberto Leycester 7 Alicie
coci consorti sue
'Roberti de '
'... ...ford Anno domini Mo CCCCmo lxx'
'Johannis Banham & caterine
anno domini millesimo CCCC'
'Adam Scherynton
Mariana uxor eius

binding.p: Traces of a pre-18th century binding visible as damage to ff. 192r-[193] verso. Small dots of cupric oxidation visible along the fore edge of the leaves probably caused by fastenings on an old binding. Damage to upper and lower margins now repaired with conservation-paper probably caused by metal book furniture such as staples for a chained binding.

origin.origDate: Written in the 15th century. Folio 192r contains a copy of a letter dated to 1400 and annotations on folios 192v-[193] recto contain 15th century dates.
origin.origPlace: Written in England. Several English names appear on the leaves.

history.acquisition: It is probable that this bifolium (and perhaps other Parts of the volume) were a later addition to the codex. There is a 'Caucio' inscription on f. i verso dated 1330, so presumably the opening flyleaves and at least the first substantial Part of this volume (i.e., Part 2) were together at that date. These endleaves (ff. 192r-[193] verso) include a copy of a letter dated to 1400 and several nearly-illegible annotations with 15th century dates, so it is likely that these endleaves and perhaps some of the other Parts were added to the 1330 form of the volume after 1400.
